No service can “fix”people. People are not broken. Circumstances outside of their control is predominantly what tips the MH scale. But services working more collaboratively can give people the skills and resources to change their circumstances. We need to do better.  3/3

Yes MH services need investment- they have been cut year on year, but without investing equally in safe supportive places to live, life coaching, training, support to access finances etc, then we will continue to be reactive to crisis with no real preventative measures. 2/3

I hear a lot about what is good for mental health & often give advice on simple things we can do to boost it. Great if a person has a stable base, enough money to live on & a support network. For many who don’t sustaining  MH becomes lost in the struggle of day to day living. 1/3

I’m getting into rant territory now 😂😂 so will stop there. But would love to hear your views/ opinions. Tell me what works well in your field. Would love to hear any best practice ideas you have too. 
Thanks for reading. 😀
Instead, shouldn’t one assessment have 6 or 7 viewpoints from 6 or 7 experts, including that of the patient?

I mean really! Why do we put a patient through 6 or 7 separate assessments (especially patients who have experienced trauma), just so each discipline gets to complete their assessment for their intervention?
MDT working should be the norm not the exception. Each member of the team working in a way that facilitates the specialities adding their parts to the overall assessment.

My opinion is that despite so much evidence suggesting MDT working has better outcomes for patient experience and outcomes we are still in practice really not great at being inclusive of everyone’s expertise, and this needs to change.

The mental health act itself is also a barrier as ultimately there will always be a responsible clinician. That some (not all I hasten to add), clinicians feel is a barrier to MDT working and co-production when ultimately they are the ones who will be held accountable.

In real terms there has to be a buy in from all members of the MDT to make it work yet we still have a very medically led service in psychiatry, that in some instances makes it very difficult to facilitate a change to the status quo.

So, in real practice why is this way of working, so difficult to achieve?  
Lots of working in silo’s with little feeding back, daunting for some patients to meet the whole MDT in one setting if we invited all to reviews. Workload pressures of teams preventing attendance anyway.

Next point, as a non-medical clinical lead being a member of a multi-disciplinary team full of expertise is essential & helps give a 360 view of how we can support the patient to achieve their outcomes. I like to think that we all have an equally valuable view of support needed.

First point, and I’d appreciate your views - the patient is a member of the MDT, as we encourage co-production patients own expertise is of great value, and we should be equally embracing input from all members.

So, I rarely talk about work as inevitably talking about working with patients skates too close to their confidentiality for me to be comfortable with it. But I would like to talk a little about MDT working. Something I’m quite passionate about. So here is a bit of a thread.🧵
